Hey, 

I (23F) totally get what your feeling. I went through something like this before and currently am . The first time was a guy friend who had a hard time getting over his ex back in is country. It had been 5 years since he seen her, but he felt shitty for leaving her. I began to have feelings for him, yet I noticed he dropped random info about her, or say that she was so pretty... etc. Now looking back I still pursued him when I should have stopped.

Even now with a new guy I like. He‚Äôs dropped two random comments about his ex and even showed me the apartment they used to live in together. So now I‚Äôm just paying attention to see what he brings up about her, at random.

My advice is to precede with caution. Pay attention to how often he talks or mentions her, or if something prompts him to talk about her. It will help you gage where he‚Äôs at emotionally. Six years is a long time and a lot of someone‚Äôs life you were connected to.

But also keep this in mind. Us girls have done the same thing too. I know I have. The guy I like right now, I used to talk about the previous guy I mentioned first to him a lot. I‚Äôd say that I‚Äôm over that guy and I‚Äôm moving on and that I have no time for games. But I‚Äôd still talk about him. Now it‚Äôs been 2/3 months since I last mentioned that guy to the guy I like now, because were are no longer in each other‚Äôs lives as friends.

When the new guy I liked started bringing up his ex, a red flag went off in my head, but I realized I spent weeks telling this new guy about my ex guy. So now I understand his pain, and process in trying to move on. 

Have empathy for him, regardless. Procede with caution. Pay attention to what he says and how. Give him room to breathe. Yet understand what you what and need right now. If he can‚Äôt give you that it‚Äôs ok. You don‚Äôt want to be his rebound. Let him find someone else for that. And if you really like him, He‚Äôs not going to fall for the rebound at the end of the day, trust me. I‚Äôve been the rebound for three years.

At best take a step back and be his friend at the end of the day. He will remember that more then anything and one day he‚Äôll realize you didn‚Äôt pressure him to move on, and you respect yourself to not throw yourself in his path. He will come around one way or another, as a great friend or more then a friend.

That‚Äôs what I‚Äôm doing with the new guy I like right now. It‚Äôs tough cause I like him, and he‚Äôs probably seeing some other girl. But I know I don‚Äôt want to be that rebound, and I hold myself to that. He‚Äôs still worthy of a friend and I can offer him that. Let‚Äôs see what happens.
